[[File:Ägyptisches Museum Kairo 2016-03-29 Ka-aper 01.jpg|thumb|Closeup of Kaaper's statue CG 34]]
'''Kaaper'''<ref name=lloyd>{{cite book |last=Sourouzian |first=Hourig|editor-last= Lloyd |editor-first= Alan B. |title= A Companion to Ancient Egypt, Volume I |url= |location= |publisher= Wiley-Blackwell|date=2010 |pages= |chapter= Old Kingdom Sculpture |isbn=978 1 4051 5598 4}}, pp.&nbsp;874-5</ref> or '''Ka’aper''',<ref name=rice>{{cite book |last=Rice |first=Michael|title= Who's Who in Ancient Egypt |url= |location= London and New York|publisher= Routledge|date=1999 |pages= |isbn=0-203-44328-4}}, pp.&nbsp;86-7</ref> also commonly known as '''Sheikh el-Beled''', was an [[ancient Egypt]]ian [[Scribe#Ancient Egypt|scribe]] and priest who lived between the late [[4th Dynasty]] and the early [[5th Dynasty]] (around 2500 BCE).<ref name=rice/> Despite his rank being not among the highest, he is well known for his famous wooden statue.

Little is known of Kaaper's life; his titles were ''[[lector priest]]'' and ''army scribe of the King'', the latter possibly linked to some military campaigns in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].<ref name=lloyd/> His [[mastaba]] (named "Saqqara C8") was discovered by [[Auguste Mariette]] in the [[Saqqara]] necropolis, just north of the [[Step Pyramid of Djoser|Step Pyramid]] of [[Djoser]]. During the excavation, the Egyptian diggers unearthed the statue and, apparently impressed by its exceptional realism, they called it ''[[Sheikh]] el-Beled'' ([[Arabic language|Arabic]] for "Headman of the village") likely because of a certain similarity between the statue and their local [[Elder (administrative title)|elder]].<ref name=lloyd/><ref name=rice/> The statue – located in the Cairo [[Egyptian Museum]], CG 34 – is {{convert|112|cm|ft|2}} tall and carved from [[Ficus sycomorus|sycamore]] wood, and depicts the corpulent Kaaper while walking with a staff. The statue's round, peaceful face is almost lifelike thanks to the eyes, which were made using [[rock crystal]] and small [[copper]] plates;<ref name=rice/> it is often cited as an example of the remarkable level of craftmanship and realism  achieved during the late 4th Dynasty.<ref name=lloyd/> From the same mastaba also came a wooden statue of a woman, commonly considered as Kaaper's wife (CG 33).<ref name=lloyd/>

