{{Infobox book | name = ''Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium'' | image = Cover_of_the_book_Psychic_Blues,_Confessions_of_a_Conflicted_Medium_by_Mark_Edward.jpg | caption = ''Psychic Blues'' cover | author = [[Mark Edward]] | language = English | cover_artist = [[Sean Tejaratchi]] | subjects = [[Psychic reading|Psychic Reading]] | publisher = [[Feral House]] | release_date = August 7, 2012 | media_type = Print ([[Paperback]]) | pages = 340 | size_weight = | isbn = 978-1-936239-27-6 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= }}
'''''Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium''''' is a memoir by [[Mark Edward]] about his time working as a psychic entertainer. Published in 2012, the book covers Edward's controversial career as both a performer and a skeptical activist.
==Overview== Mark Edward gives the reader a look into the world of the psychic entertainer. From working the overnight shift answering the telephone for the [[Psychic Friends Network]]<ref name="Feral House">{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|authorlink=Mark Edward|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=11–43|chapter=Chapter II: The 900 Years}}</ref><ref name=Skepticality186 /> to counseling the rich and famous at celebrity galas,<ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=195–215|chapter=Chapter X: The Celebrity Syndrome}}</ref><ref name=NewYorkTimes /> the author paints a picture of what it is really like to work in this profession. The book was published in paperback format in 2012 by [[Feral House]]. In 2015, Edward announced plans for the production of an [[audiobook]] version containing a substantial amount of additional material about his influences, personal life, and motivations.<ref name="MMT">{{Cite episode |title=Aug 20 2015 Psychic Blues - Mark Edward Interview| url=https://soundcloud.com/wgdr/the-magical-mystery-tour-aug-20-2015-psychic-blues-mark-edward-interview |access-date=27 Jan 2016 |series=The Magical Mystery Tour | |first= |last=Tonio |station=WGDR |location=Hardwick, VT |date=20 August 2015 |time=45:43 |language=English}}</ref>
{{quote|text=This book contains only my observations of the psychic world in its most likely paradigm: a terribly disappointing con.|sign=Mark Edward|source=page xiii}}
==About the author== {{main|Mark Edward}} [[File:Mark Edward Book Signing.jpg|thumb|upright|left| Mark Edward at a book signing]] Mark Edward (born Mark Edward Wilson)<ref name=NewYorkTimes>{{cite web|last1=Oppenheimer|first1=Mark|title=Pro Medium Repents for Life of Cons|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/01/us/in-book-mark-edward-tells-tricks-used-as-a-medium.html?_r=1|website=New York Times|accessdate=8 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107163405/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/01/us/in-book-mark-edward-tells-tricks-used-as-a-medium.html?_r=1|archivedate=7 November 2012|date=31 August 2012}}</ref> first acquired an interest in performing and magic from his grandfather, who was a [[Magic (illusion)|magician]] himself.<ref name="Skepticality186">{{cite podcast|url=http://www.skepticality.com/|title=Skepticality Episode 186|website= |publisher=Skeptic Magazine|host=[[Derek Colanduno]]|date=3 July 2012|time= |access-date=5 December 2015}}</ref> His career as a performer began in the 1970s,<ref name=NewYorkTimes /><ref name=PineCone /> and has included 14 years at [[The Magic Castle]], where he gave [[palmistry]] and [[tarot]] readings and conducted [[séance]]s.<ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=1–9|chapter=Chapter I Illusions Aside}}</ref> He has also performed at a wide variety of venues, including private homes,<ref name=PineCone /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=157–166|chapter=Chapter VII Very Private Readings}}</ref> a [[Spiritualism|spiritualist]] church,<ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=111–156|chapter=Chapter VI The OC Occultist}}</ref> corporate events,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=179–194|chapter=Chapter IX Ladies' Night}}</ref><ref name=DailyMail>{{cite web|last1=Russell|first1=Scarlett|title=The supernatural swindlers! Whistle-blower exposes how bogus mediums con believers out of thousands by pretending to have psychic powers|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2617659/The-supernatural-swindlers-Whistle-blower-exposes-psychics-believers-thousands-making-think-theyre-talking-dead-loved-ones.html|website=Daily Mail|archive-date=4 May 2014|accessdate=8 December 2015|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140504153134/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2617659/The-supernatural-swindlers-Whistle-blower-exposes-psychics-believers-thousands-making-think-theyre-talking-dead-loved-ones.html|date=1 May 2014}}</ref> celebrity parties (including a baby shower at [[Eddie Murphy|Eddie Murphy’s]] house and [[Buddy Hackett]]'s 70th birthday party),<ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref name=NewYorkTimes /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=195–215|chapter=Chapter X The Celebrity Syndrome}}</ref> and large public gatherings such as [[Dragon Con]].<ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref name=DragonConBookTest>{{cite web|last1=Gerbic|first1=Susan|authorlink=Susan Gerbic|title=James Randi Book Test @ Dragon*Con 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7p2gWJ0ojoA|website=YouTube|accessdate=9 December 2015|date=6 September 2012}}</ref> His work with the [[Psychic Friends Network]] led him to the conclusion that all psychic entertainers were using only natural techniques, and that the public would be better served by his revealing these techniques.<ref name="Feral House"/><ref name=Skepticality186 /><ref name=NewYorkTimes /><ref name=PineCone /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Edward|first1=Mark|title=Psychic Blues: Confessions of a Conflicted Medium|date=2012|publisher=Feral House|location=Port Townsend, WA|isbn=978-1-936239-27-6|pages=45–77|chapter=Chapter III World's Greatest}}</ref>
{{clear}}
==Reception== [[File:Photo Shoot for NYT.jpg|thumb|upright|Photo Shoot for ''[[The New York Times]]'']] Mark Oppenheimer of ''[[The New York Times]]'' placed Edward's book in the tradition of other performers—such as [[James Randi]], [[Harry Houdini]], and [[Penn & Teller]]—who simultaneously "perform their crafts and debunk them".<ref name=NewYorkTimes /> Oppenheimer also commented on the "conflicted" nature of the book, saying, "there is something tragic about his own ambivalence. From page to page, he cannot decide which side he is on. Sometimes he is crusading against the mountebanks and charlatans. Other times he defends his work as pure entertainment."<ref name=NewYorkTimes /> He called the book, "A strange mishmash of self-pity, self-justification, and genuine repentance—and a compelling look at the disputed territory where entertainment meets religion, where some practitioners actually think they can practice both at the same time."<ref name=NewYorkTimes />
The subject matter of this book caused [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV's]] program [[This Morning (TV programme)|''This Morning'']] to invite Edward to speak about "supernatural swindlers" on May 1, 2014.<ref name=DailyMail /><ref name=ITV>{{cite web|title=A Supernatural Swindler |url=http://www.itv.com/thismorning/hot-topics/supernatural-week-psychic-conman-mark |website=ITV |accessdate=8 December 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726205121/http://www.itv.com/thismorning/hot-topics/supernatural-week-psychic-conman-mark |archivedate=July 26, 2015 |date=1 May 2014 |deadurl=unfit }}</ref>
A [[Carmel-by-the-Sea, California|''Carmel'']] ''Pine Cone'' newspaper article noted, "The book has stirred up attention both in the United States and abroad", and, "His message is that so-called psychics don’t have supernatural powers—they're just master manipulators and are well versed in saying what people want to hear—and that most of them are simply frauds."<ref name=PineCone>{{cite news|last1=Harmon|first1=Rachel|title=Secrets of Psychics to be Revealed|url=http://www.pineconearchive.com/downloads120921.html|accessdate=9 December 2015|issue=Vol. 98 No. 38|date=September 21, 2012|pages=12A}}</ref>
[[Skepticism|Skeptical]] activist and [[podcast]]er John Rael<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.skepticality.com/about-us/|website=Skepticality|accessdate=8 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907204613/http://www.skepticality.com/about-us/|archivedate=7 September 2015}}</ref> also recognized the dual nature of the book. Writing in a Skeptic.com book review, Rael chided Edward for continuing to perform as a psychic entertainer while still recognizing the value of the book itself. “The greatest tragedy of this book is that Edward seems to miss out on his own lesson, and it’s a really good one: . . . that we should listen to each other and talk to each other much more than we do."<ref name=Rael>{{cite web|last1=Rael|first1=John|title=Inside the Psychic Mind|url=http://www.skeptic.com/eskeptic/13-08-21/|website=Skeptic.com|accessdate=8 December 2015|date=21 August 2013}}</ref> Of the book, Rael said: "[D]o you want to learn about psychics? The people, not the tricks? Do you want to understand who psychics are and not just how they operate? Here is your book."<ref name=Rael />
Writing for ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'', [[Ray Hyman]] acknowledged Edward's "ambiguous role in the skeptical community,"<ref name=Hyman>{{cite journal|last1=Hyman|first1=Ray|authorlink=Ray Hyman|title=An Inside Look at a 'Psychic's' World|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=November 2013|volume=37|issue=6|pages=57–58}}</ref> stating that, "He is quite active in helping skeptical groups test psychic claims and debunk obviously phony psychics who exploit their clients. At the same time, Edward still performs as a 'psychic.' He does not claim to have psychic powers. On the other hand, he does not openly disclaim such powers."<ref name=Hyman /> Of the book itself, Hyman said, "Because it provides us a rare insight into a psychic's world, as well as raising some important ethical issues for skeptics to ponder, I highly recommend every skeptic carefully read and ponder this book's contents."<ref name=Hyman />
