{{Other uses|Surrogate (disambiguation)}}
'''Surrogate''' (from [[Latin language|Lat.]] ''surrogare'', to substitute for), a deputy of a [[bishop]] or an [[ecclesiastical judge]], acting in the absence of his principal and strictly bound by the authority of the latter.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Surrogate |volume=26 |page=141 |inline=1}}</ref>
Canon 128 of the canons of 1603 lays down the qualifications necessary for the office of surrogate and canon 123 the regulations for the appointment to the office. At present the chief duty of a surrogate in England is the granting of marriage licences, but judgments of the arches court of [[Canterbury]] have been delivered by a surrogate in the absence of the official principal.<ref name=EB1911/>
